3 On the other hand, it may happen that to use such a mode of speech is not only unbecoming, but wicked ; for example, when the honour due to God or the love due to our neighbour, or the reve- rence due to a superior, or the nature of the matter, requires us to say what we have in our mind 2 as in contracts, we have said that all is to be disclosed which the nature of a contract is understood to require; in which sense we very properly understand that of Cicero, that lying must altogether be taken away from contracts: in which case Zyiny is, it would seem, to be understood so laxly as to include even obscure language3 which however we have excluded from our notion of a lie.
